Framework for PV fault detection and Clustering¶

This notebook presents an algorithm for building a photovoltaic (PV) digital twin (DT) that models expected power output under normal operating conditions. By comparing measured PV data against DT estimates, the framework detects significant deviations as abnormalities. Extended abnormalities are categorized as faults, with their severity quantified and archived in a specialized fault database. Unsupervised clustering then groups faults by impact similarity, enabling rapid comparison of new faults to historical analogs within the same cluster for targeted diagnostics and maintenance planning.

The data used are originated from the open source datasets provided from NIST and can be obtained for the following link:

https://pvdata.nist.gov/

The NIST Roof system is a 73~kWp single-orientation installation, featuring south-facing modules mounted at a $10^\circ$ tilt angle on a building rooftop within the NIST premises. Notably, the northern section of the modules exhibits a $0.5^\circ$ clockwise azimuthal offset. The system is powered by a Satcon PVS-75 480 inverter with a 75~kW output capacity. Module strings are combined in parallel at four combiner boxes, forming four output circuits that connect to the inverter.

Developing the PV output estimation model¶

To enable effective fault detection, we develop estimation models that replicate the expected behavior of the PV system under healthy operating conditions. These models serve as baselines for identifying deviations in real-time measurements.

A dedicated model is trained for each measured parameter:

  • Current Estimation Models: Four separate models, one for each combiner box current, to capture string-level variations.
  • Voltage Estimation Model: A single model for the common DC voltage across all combiner boxes, leveraging the parallel connection that ensures uniform voltage distribution.

These models are regression-based and trained on historical healthy data, with inputs including $G_{PoA}$ and $T_{PV}$. Residuals between predicted and actual values will later flag potential anomalies.

Data Filtering for Training PV Output Estimation Models¶

Prior to training the PV output estimation models, it is crucial to select high-quality data from periods when the system operated under fully healthy conditions. Naively discarding data based on deviations from expected performance is problematic without prior models, as it risks excluding valid low-irradiance measurements (e.g., early morning or late afternoon) that are not indicative of faults.

To address this, we apply two complementary filters to identify and retain only reliable data:

  • Daily Pearson Correlation Coefficient ($R^2$): Compute the Pearson correlation between the maximum power point current $I_{MPP}$ and $G_{PoA}$ for each day. Under healthy conditions, this value is expected to be very high (close to 1), as $I_{MPP}$ is directly driven from the $G_{PoA}$ with minimal influence from $T_{PV}$.
  • Daily Performance Ratio for Current ($PR_{I}$): Calculate the ratio $PR_{I}$ = Σ($I_{MPP}$) / Σ($G_{PoA}$ aggregated over each day. This metric detects overall underperformance, particularly in scenarios where partial system failures (e.g., one combiner box offline) maintain high correlation but reduce total output.

# Example of the filltering process

# Pearson r filter
target_current = 'Ishunt 1'
threshold_pearson_r = 0.98 # empirically defined
PRI_threshold = (0.75, 1.25) # empirically defined

df_daily_filter = df.resample('1D').apply(lambda x: x[['Gpoa', target_current]].corr().iloc[0,1]).to_frame('pearsor_r')
df_daily_filter['good_pearson_r'] = df_daily_filter['pearsor_r'] > threshold_pearson_r

# PRI filter
df_PRI = df[['Gpoa', target_current]].resample('D').sum()
df_PRI['PRI'] = df_PRI[target_current] / df_PRI['Gpoa']
df_PRI.drop(columns = ['Gpoa', target_current], inplace = True)

df_PRI = df_PRI / df_PRI.median()
df_daily_filter['PRI'] = df_PRI['PRI']
df_daily_filter['good_PRI'] = (df_daily_filter['PRI'] > PRI_threshold[0]) & (df_daily_filter['PRI'] < PRI_threshold[1])
df_daily_filter['good_day'] = df_daily_filter['good_PRI'] & df_daily_filter['good_pearson_r']

To ensure the integrity of training data for each individual combiner box (string), we apply the filtering process separately for every string. This approach accounts for scenarios where faults may affect only specific strings, rendering them dysfunctional, while others remain fully operational on the same day. By isolating per-string filters, we maximize the usable healthy data for training the corresponding current estimation models, avoiding the pitfalls of global aggregation.

In [6]:
def get_good_days_list(target_current, pearson_r_threshold = 0.98, PRI_thresholds = (0.75, 1.25)):
    df_daily_filter = df.resample('D').apply(lambda x: x[['Gpoa', target_current]].corr().iloc[0, 1]).to_frame(name='pearson_r')
    df_PRI = df[['Gpoa', target_current]].resample('D').sum()
    df_PRI['PRI'] = df_PRI[target_current] / df_PRI['Gpoa']
    df_PRI['PRI'] = df_PRI['PRI'] / df_PRI['PRI'].median()
    df_daily_filter['PRI'] = df_PRI['PRI']
    df_daily_filter['good_pearson_r'] = df_daily_filter['pearson_r'] > pearson_r_threshold
    df_daily_filter['good_PRI'] = (df_daily_filter['PRI'] > PRI_thresholds[0]) & (df_daily_filter['PRI'] < PRI_thresholds[1])
    df_daily_filter['good_day'] = df_daily_filter['good_pearson_r'] & df_daily_filter['good_PRI']
    good_days_list = df_daily_filter.index[df_daily_filter['good_day']].to_list()
    return good_days_list

good_days_dict = {}

for i in range(1, 5):
    good_days_dict[f'Ishunt {i}'] = get_good_days_list(f'Ishunt {i}')

For the common DC voltage shared across all combiner boxes due to the parallel configuration, we select days where all strings are fully functional. This ensures a robust, system-wide healthy baseline, avoiding contamination from partial faults in any individual string.

We utilize data from 2015, as it provides adequate volumes for effective model training while representing typical operational conditions.

Scaling the input data¶

Prior to training the PV output estimation models, we standardize the input features using scikit-learn's StandardScaler. This technique centers the data by subtracting the mean and scales it to unit variance, promoting numerical stability and equitable feature contributions across varying magnitudes.

Given the distinct behavioral patterns of each target variable, we employ a dedicated scaler instance for the inputs of every model, four for the combiner box currents and one for the common DC voltage. This approach avoids cross-contamination and enhances model performance tailored to each output.

In [102]:
scalers = {}
scaled_training_data_dict = {}

for key, df_train in training_data_dict.items():
    scaler = StandardScaler()
    X = df_train[input_data_columns]
    X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)
    scaled_training_data = df_train.copy()
    scaled_training_data[input_data_columns] = X_scaled
    scaled_training_data_dict[key] = scaled_training_data.copy()
    scalers[key] = scaler

Following data preparation and scaling, we employ deep learning architecture such as Multi-Layer Perceptrons (MLPs) networks, to train the four current estimation models. These models learn non-linear relationships between inputs and the target currents, capturing subtle patterns in healthy PV behavior.

Hyperparameters (e.g., layer sizes, learning rates, epochs) are empirically determined through experimentation (details omitted for brevity). These values provide a solid starting point but can be further optimized.

Fault detection¶

Faults are identified by detecting significant deviations between the expected (modeled) and actual measured performance of the PV system.

In [14]:
def get_estimations(inputs, scaler, model):
    X_scaled = scaler.transform(inputs)
    return model.predict(X_scaled)

df_inputs = df[input_data_columns].dropna()
df_predictions = pd.DataFrame(index = df_inputs.index)

for target_value in models.keys():
    df_predictions[target_value] = get_estimations(df_inputs, scaler=scalers[target_value], model= models[target_value])

df_ratios = pd.concat([(df[target_value] / df_predictions[target_value]).to_frame(target_value) for target_value in models.keys()], axis = 1).dropna()
df_power_ratios = pd.DataFrame(index = df_ratios.index)

for i in range(1, 5):
    df_power_ratios[f'PI_{i}'] = df_ratios[f'Ishunt {i}'] * df_ratios['Vmpp']

Determine threshold¶

To define "significant deviations," we establish data-driven thresholds based on the statistical properties of performance ratios computed from healthy training data (using the prior filtering criteria).

Threshold Calculation Process¶

  1. Compute Performance Ratios: For filtered healthy data, calculate ratios, for power ($PPI_{i}$) using the trained models.
  2. Remove Low-Irradiance Instances: Exclude measurements where $G_{PoA}$ < 200 W/m² to avoid non-linear effects that skew variability.
  3. Calculate Statistics: For each ratio
  • Median (μ): Central tendency under healthy conditions
  • Standard Deviation (σ): Natural variability
  1. Set Thresholds: Define fault thresholds as:
  • $Threshold_{i}$ = $μ_{PPI}$ - 2 × $σ_{PPI}$ (for i = 1,2,3,4)
In [15]:
df_good_power_ratio_dates = df_power_ratios.copy()

df_good_power_ratio_dates['date'] = pd.to_datetime(df_good_power_ratio_dates.index.date)

df_good_power_ratio_dates = df_good_power_ratio_dates.loc[df_good_power_ratio_dates['date'].isin(common_good_days)]

df_good_power_ratio_dates['Gpoa'] = df['Gpoa']

df_good_power_ratio_dates = df_good_power_ratio_dates.query('Gpoa > 200')

PI_thresholds = {i : df_good_power_ratio_dates[f'PI_{i}'].median() - 2 * df_good_power_ratio_dates[f'PI_{i}'].std() for i in range(1, 5)}

Identify anlomalies and faults¶

Using the predefined thresholds, we systematically detect anomalies and classify persistent events as faults. This two-stage process ensures only meaningful, sustained deviations trigger maintenance alerts.

Detection Process¶

  1. Anomaly Identification: For all time steps where $G_{PoA}$ < 200 W/m²
  2. Fault Classification: For each anomalous day
  • Calculate Duration: Sum consecutive anomaly time steps for each string/voltage
  • Classify as Fault: If duration > 2 hours (empirical threshold based on typical fault persistence vs. transient events)
In [16]:
df_power_ratios_anomalies = df_power_ratios.copy()

df_power_ratios_anomalies['Gpoa'] = df['Gpoa']

df_power_ratios_anomalies = df_power_ratios_anomalies.query('Gpoa > 200').drop(columns = 'Gpoa')

for i in range(1, 5):
    df_power_ratios_anomalies[f'PI_{i}'] = df_power_ratios_anomalies[f'PI_{i}'] < PI_thresholds[i]


data_resolution = np.median(np.diff(df.index))
fault_duration_threshold = pd.Timedelta(hours = 2)

fault_timestamps = {}

for i in range(1, 5):
    df_alert = (df_power_ratios[[f'PI_{i}']] < PI_thresholds[i]).query(f'PI_{i} == True')
    downtime = df_alert.resample('1D').sum() * data_resolution > fault_duration_threshold
    fault_elegible_days = downtime.query(f'PI_{i} == True').index

    df_alert['date'] = pd.to_datetime(df_alert.index.date)
    fault_timestamps[i] = df_alert.loc[df_alert['date'].isin(fault_elegible_days)].index

Fault signature formulation¶

Once faults are identified and labeled within the time series, we extract and compile their quantitative impact profiles, the performance ratios during fault periods into structured fault signatures. These signatures serve as compact, interpretable feature vectors for subsequent clustering.

  • Imperfect output estimation in the deep learning/XGBoost models
  • Transitional states in the data (e.g., MPPT hunting, brief shading)

To enhance cluster separability, we apply a Low-Pass Filter (LPF) to smooth the fault signatures, using rolling standard deviation (STD) and rolling median functions to effectively denoise fault signatures while preserving true fault patterns

In [22]:
std_threshold = 0.05
window = '60T'
min_samples = 30

fault_signatures_dict_clean = {}


for i in range(1, 5):
    df_fs_std = fault_signatures_dict[i].rolling(window, min_periods = min_samples, center = True).std().dropna()
    df_fs_median = fault_signatures_dict[i].rolling(window, min_periods = min_samples, center = True).median().dropna()


    df_fs_std['max_value'] = df_fs_std.apply(np.max, axis = 1)
    df_fs_std = df_fs_std.loc[df_fs_std['max_value'] < std_threshold]
    df_fs_clean = df_fs_median.loc[df_fs_median.index.isin(df_fs_std.index)]

    fault_signatures_dict_clean[i] = df_fs_clean.copy()

Result: Clean, stable fault signatures with clear separation between fault types (e.g., string disconnects, overvoltage), ideal for clustering.

Fault Clustering¶

With noise-reduced fault signatures in hand, we now apply unsupervised clustering to group faults exhibiting similar impact patterns. This reveals distinct failure modes for targeted diagnostics and maintenance.

In [24]:
def make_clusters(X, min_cluster_size=4, cluster_selection_epsilon=0.1):
    clusterer = HDBSCAN(min_cluster_size=min_cluster_size, cluster_selection_epsilon=cluster_selection_epsilon)
    labels = clusterer.fit_predict(X)
    return labels

Practical Application Scenario¶

How This Framework Enables Real-World Troubleshooting¶

When a new fault occurs, the framework provides immediate diagnostic insights by:

  1. Extract Signature: Extract the fault signature from real-time data
  2. Cluster Assignment: Predict cluster membership using the trained model
  3. Historical Analysis: Review similar past faults in the same cluster
  4. Accelerated Resolution: Leverage documentation/patterns for faster troubleshooting

Real-World Example: January 5, 2017¶

Scenario: Late evening alert - Voltage drop across ALL combiner boxes (CBs) while currents remain at expected levels.

In [100]:
# articluate the impact of the fault on each combiner box

prompt = f'''

I need you to help me to identify the possible causes of a fault observed in a PV system.

The PV system is a 73~kWp single-orientation installation, featuring south-facing modules mounted at a $10^\circ$ tilt angle on a building rooftop within the NIST premises. Notably, the northern section of the modules exhibits a $0.5^\circ$ clockwise azimuthal offset. The system is powered by a Satcon PVS-75 480 inverter with a 75~kW output capacity. Module strings are combined in parallel at four combiner boxes, forming four output circuits that connect to the inverter.

'''

volatge_change = np.mean([impact_analysis_per_CB[key]['Vmpp'] for key in impact_analysis_per_CB])

prompt += f'\nThe system voltage (Vmp) has changed by {volatge_change:.2f}% during the fault.\n'

for key in range(1, 5):
    current_change = impact_analysis_per_CB[key][f'Ishunt {key}']

    prompt += f'Combiner box {key}: Current (Ishunt) changed by {current_change:.2f}%.\n'

average_temperature_during_fault = df.loc['2017-01-5', 'Tpv'].mean()

prompt += f'The average module temperature during the fault was {average_temperature_during_fault:.2f}°C.\n'

prompt
Out[101]:
'\n\nI need you to help me to identify the possible causes of a fault observed in a PV system.\n\nThe PV system is a 73~kWp single-orientation installation, featuring south-facing modules mounted at a $10^\\circ$ tilt angle on a building rooftop within the NIST premises. Notably, the northern section of the modules exhibits a $0.5^\\circ$ clockwise azimuthal offset. The system is powered by a Satcon PVS-75 480 inverter with a 75~kW output capacity. Module strings are combined in parallel at four combiner boxes, forming four output circuits that connect to the inverter.\n\n\nThe system voltage (Vmp) has changed by -19.27% during the fault.\nCombiner box 1: Current (Ishunt) changed by 6.45%.\nCombiner box 2: Current (Ishunt) changed by 6.58%.\nCombiner box 3: Current (Ishunt) changed by 7.03%.\nCombiner box 4: Current (Ishunt) changed by 6.77%.\nThe average module temperature during the fault was -1.31°C.\n'

We provide the above prompt to GenAI (manually or automatically), and the AI agent returns a possible diagnosis. In this case, the response was as follows:

  1. Primary Cause: Transient MPPT Tracking Error Due to Low Inverter Internal TemperatureWhy it fits: The Satcon PVS-75's MPPT algorithm can exhibit instability or "hunting" in extreme cold due to sensor drift (e.g., voltage/current transducers) or internal air temperature thresholds, forcing operation at a lower Vmp to avoid perceived instability. This yields the exact symptom profile: Vmp plummets as the tracker biases toward higher current (near-flat I-V knee region), with Imp/Ishunt rising slightly (~5-10%) as compensation. No full shutdown occurs if it's a marginal condition, matching the continued (albeit suboptimal) operation. NIST's high-speed monitoring logs such events via InvVoltageFault and TemperatureFaults codes, which capture transient undervoltages and low-temp triggers without permanent damage. Temperature relevance: At -1.31°C modules (inverter internal air likely similar or lower, per NIST's InvTempInternalAir_C metric), the unit hits low-temp warning thresholds (e.g., codes 89-90: internal/inverter air low temp), derating MPPT sweep efficiency. Overnight warmup clears it automatically, as faults auto-resolve above trip levels. System-specific factors: The Satcon's single-MPPT design is sensitive to uniform array changes; the ~60m cable run to the inverter (per NIST layout) amplifies any cold-induced resistance variability. Older firmware (common in 2010s installs) lacks robust cold-weather adaptations. Diagnosis/confirmation steps:Review NIST logs for the fault timestamp: Check NumActiveFaults, InvVoltageFault, and InvTempInternalAir_C—a spike in low-temp codes with Vmp anomaly confirms. Query inverter HMI/Modbus for historical fault 89/90; perform cold-soak test (simulate -5°C) to replicate. Compare MPPT efficiency pre/post-fault using irradiance-normalized data.

Mitigation: Add inverter enclosure insulation/heater (e.g., 50W strip heater, thermostat-controlled at 5°C). Update firmware if available; monitor via SolarVU or similar for proactive alerts.

  1. Secondary Cause: Temporary Increase in Series Resistance (Rs) from Cold-Induced Moisture/CondensationWhy it fits: Overnight dew or light frost (common at low tilt on rooftops) can condense in MC4 connectors or combiner boxes, spiking Rs transiently (~2-5 Ω effective) and shifting the MPP leftward on the I-V curve—dropping Vmp sharply while Imp edges up. Uniformity across combiners suggests array-wide exposure (e.g., morning fog at NIST Gaithersburg). Warming evaporates moisture, restoring values by next day. Temperature relevance: Sub-zero modules promote condensation below dew point; the 10° tilt retains it longer than steeper angles. System-specific factors: NIST cameras (5-min intervals) often capture frost/snow; the northern 0.5° offset may slightly alter microclimate but not enough for non-uniformity. Diagnosis/confirmation steps:Correlate with NIST weather logs (dew point vs. temp); inspect camera images for frost on modules/connectors. Measure Rs pre/post-chill using a curve tracer; thermal imaging for cold spots at junctions.

Mitigation: Apply dielectric grease to connectors; add IP67 enclosures or tilted drip trays at combiners. Schedule winter de-icing (e.g., NIST's ethanol method for sensors).

  1. Less Likely: Sensor or Communication Glitch in Data Acquisition System (DAS)Why it fits: NIST's Roof DAS experiences frequent comms drops (every few days), requiring resets, which could artifactually log a "fault" via skewed V/I readings during brief outages. However, the consistent multi-combiner Ishunt rise makes this less probable than a true electrical event. Temperature relevance: Cold stiffens cabling, worsening intermittent RS-485 links. System-specific factors: Ring-buffer storage overwrites old data, but high-utilization resets align with transients. Diagnosis/confirmation steps: Check DAS CkBatt or ChgState for concurrent low-battery faults; validate against redundant GHI/RTD sensors. Mitigation: Upgrade to fiber optics for RS-485; automate resets via NIST's relay.
